
xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
ENGLISH VERSION
xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx


With the homology command, we can search whether the GenBank ID
accessed by the user is associated with similar proteins by sequence alignment
in the RefSeq Protein database, using NCBI facilities, such as UniGen, Gene
and homoloGene.

The first step consists of searching for similar proteins in several organisms,
e.g.,

	$ homology.sh -i AF002173.1 -l
		O.latipes
		T.rubripes
		D.rerio
	
Later, the user can choose the specific species of interest and obtain data from
the search, such as the percentage homology, prot ID, name and Gene ID.

* Input file format: The species name comes at the end of the command and
only the first word used is in uppercase, corresponding to the genus, followed
by a point and then the species name in lowercase. Spaces should not be used.

The options for the last command are shown here:

	$ homology.sh -i AF002173.1 -s D.rerio
           UniGeneTrout: 2897711
           Omy: 35863
	     D.rerio
             gbID: AF002173.1
             protID: NP_956700.1
             protName: hypothetical_protein_LOC393377
             ld: 54.5
             len: 345
             geneURL: /sites/entrez?db=protein&cmd=Link&LinkName=protein_gene&from_uid=57528839
             geneID: 393377
             geneSym:
			
As can be seen, the output file includes the URL from which the data is
reported, which may be useful if the user wants to verify or find additional
related data.

If there are enough genes, the results are saved directly to a file with an
extension “.out”, which can be viewed with WordPad or a similar programme.

The getAll.sh command can be used to obtain extended data from an input
file that can be processed. The format of the gene input file should be the
GenBank IDs, organized in a single column and saved in text format (“.txt”). The
command to use is:

$ ./getAll.sh SelectedSpecie > OutputFileName.out

e.g., $ ./getAll.sh D.rerio > Omy-Dre.out
			
			
xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
VERSION EN CASTELLANO	
xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx


El comando homology, permite consultar en diferentes bases de datos del NCBI tales como UniGen, Gene y EST, si el GeneBankID del
gen que es consultado por el usuario presentan proteinas similares al comparar a través de RefSeq Proteins grupos de transcripción, ya que 
las alineaciones de las secuencias pueden sugerir la función del grupo o cluster.

La primera fase del programa consiste en buscar proteinas similares en diferentes organismos, por ejemplo:
	
	$ homology.sh -i AF002173.1 -l
	  O.latipes
	  T.rubripes
	  D.rerio
	
El usuario puede elegir la especie que prefiera, para obtener algunos datos sobre la busqueda
realizada como el porcentaje de homología, la especie elegida, el protID (proteínas), el nombre y su geneID.

	$ homology.sh -i AF002173.1 -s D.rerio
           UniGeneTrout: 2897711
           Omy: 35863
	     D.rerio
             gbID: AF002173.1
             protID: NP_956700.1
             protName: hypothetical_protein_LOC393377
             ld: 54.5
             len: 345
             geneURL: /sites/entrez?db=protein&cmd=Link&LinkName=protein_gene&from_uid=57528839
             geneID: 393377
             geneSym:
		     


	